Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one forcing idea stood out: moving the knight from f6 to e4. This move is a classical knight check—in UCI notation, that’s "f6e4". When the knight lands on e4, it immediately attacks the white king on d2 (since from e4 a knight reaches d2). This forces white to make an immediate defensive response, while you (Black) keep up the initiative in a materially superior position.

I'll now complete my turn with:

make_move f6e4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one tempting idea is to use the knight on g3. It has two immediate capturing moves:
 
• g3e2 would capture the white knight on e2—but note that the white bishop on f1 defends e2 (since from f1 it has a diagonal to e2), so after Nxe2, White could recapture immediately with Bxf1, yielding an even trade.
 
• In contrast, g3f1 captures the white bishop sitting on f1. That bishop isn’t defended by any other white piece (the white knight on e2 cannot reach f1, and neither can knight from b1 or the king on c2), so Nxf1 wins material.
 
Thus, a strong move for Black is to capture on f1 with the knight. 

make_move g3f1

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll now proceed with a move. One idea in this position is to use the advanced black queen—for example, moving it from h2 to h3 to capture the white pawn on h3. This not only wins a pawn but also places the queen on a square that is well‐defended by the bishop on c8 (which covers the c8–h3 diagonal). In case White tries to recapture on h3 with the knight, Black’s bishop will be ready to recapture, leaving White down material.

Therefore, I'll play:

make_move h2h3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, a forcing move appears to be to use the rook on h8 to give a direct check. For example, moving that rook from h8 to h4 (i.e. "h8h4") checks the white king along rank 4. After 1...h8h4 the white king’s legal moves shrink dramatically – its adjacent squares on rank 3 are covered by the rook on a3 and, along the h‐file, those squares are controlled by the checking rook. (Note that the pawn on g5 already covers f4 and h4.) In this line the only flight square is f5, which forces the white king into a very restricted position.

Thus, I will play:

make_move h8h4

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Failed to make move: illegal uci: 'h8h4' in 2k2b1r/pp2pp1p/8/6p1/1p1p2K1/r7/8/8 b - - 1 48

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current position (FEN: 2k2b1r/pp2pp1p/8/6p1/1p1p2K1/r7/8/8 b - - 1 48) and noting that the rook on h8 cannot move down because its path is blocked by the pawn on h7, one promising idea is to bring the other rook into play with a forcing check.

Consider the rook on a3. It can slide along the third rank. In particular, moving it from a3 to g3 (that is, "a3g3") places the rook on the g‐file. Since White’s king currently sits on g4, the rook on g3 would deliver an immediate check along that file. 

After 1…a3g3, let’s review White’s options. The white king on g4 would then not be able to move into any square on the g‐file (g3 and g5) and can’t go to any square on rank 3 (f3, g3, h3) because the rook controls all of rank 3. In addition, the pawn on g5 covers both f4 and h4. This leaves only f5 and h5 as potential escape squares.

While this check isn’t mate in one, it is a forcing move that significantly restricts the white king’s mobility and sets the stage for further decisive action.

I will therefore play:

make_move a3g3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll go with a winning tactical shot. Notice that the black pawn sitting on c4 can capture diagonally onto b3—and that square is occupied by White’s queen. That move, c4b3, wins the queen (even if White may recapture with the pawn from a2). In view of the huge material gain, I choose:

make_move c4b3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one strong candidate move is to develop the light‐squared bishop from c8 with check. In particular, moving it from c8 to f5 travels along the diagonal f5–e4–d3–c2 that pins white’s king on b1. To explain briefly:

• The bishop on c8 can move to f5 (since the intermediate squares d7 and e6 are empty).
• Once on f5, the bishop gives check along the diagonal toward b1.
• Because white’s king on b1 is very restricted (its only nearby legal square appears to be a2), Black forces white into a difficult situation.

Therefore, I will proceed with the move “c8f5.”

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, I’ve examined Black’s options and found a decisive mating move. In the position, Black’s queen sits on f3 and has a clear diagonal route down‐left if not for the obstacle. Notice that though the obvious idea of Qf3–h1 is tempting, the white pawn on g2 blocks that route. Instead, Black can play:

  Queen from f3 to d1

This move (written in UCI as “f3d1”) is a diagonal move (f3 → e2 → d1) with the intermediate square e2 unoccupied. Once on d1 (which is on rank 1), the queen lines up along the entire first rank. The white king on b1 then finds all adjacent escape squares covered:
  • It cannot step to a1 (occupied by Black’s bishop on a1 and would be exposed to the queen’s horizontal attack).
  • a2 and c2 are controlled by Black’s pawn on b3.
  • b2 is covered by the bishop on a1.
  • c1 falls directly on the queen’s ray along rank 1.
Furthermore, the white knight on a3 has no way to capture or interpose on a rank‑1 check.

Thus, by playing “make_move f3d1”, Black delivers checkmate.

I will now complete my turn with that move.

make_move f3d1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board you sent, one interesting idea as Black is to immediately exchange the somewhat over‐advanced bishop on h3. In the position the bishop on h3 is “en prise” after Black castles kingside (since it would then be unprotected and liable to be captured by White’s bishop on f1). By playing  ...Bxf1 , Black forces White to recapture with the king (Kxf1), which not only wins the bishop exchange (trading our bishop for White’s bishop) but also forces White’s king out of its safe position and eliminates White’s right to castle.

So, I will make the move:

make_move h3f1

This move captures the white bishop on f1.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one move that immediately gains material for Black is to use the knight on g3 to capture White’s rook on h1. In the current position the g3‐knight is under the threat of being captured by the white queen along the third rank, so moving it to h1 not only avoids that risk but also wins a rook in exchange for the knight. (After Nxh1, even though the knight finds itself in the corner, it has escape routes on f2 or back to g3 on the next move.) 

Therefore, I will play:

make_move g3h1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position you provided, one very strong candidate is to move the knight from f2 to g4. That move does two important things:
 
• It clears the diagonal from our queen on e1 so that the queen now directly eyes g3 (where the enemy king sits). (Before the knight moved, our own knight on f2 was “blocking” the queen’s sight along the e1–f2–g3–h4 diagonal.)
 
• The knight landing on g4 itself will cover one of the king’s potential escape squares (namely h2) so that when the enemy king’s only move is forced (to g2) the mating net is very tight.
 
To explain more briefly: After 1…Nf2–g4, the enemy king on g3 is in check from our queen on e1 along the newly unblocked diagonal. Its possible moves from g3 (recalling that the surrounding squares are:
  • f4 (covered by our light‐squared bishop on c1),
  • g4 (now occupied by our knight),
  • h4 (still covered by our queen),
  • f3 (covered by our knight on e5),
  • h3 (covered by our dark‐squared bishop on c8),
  • f2 (attacked by our queen),
  • h2 (now covered by our knight on g4),
  • g2 (the only remaining square)
) are almost entirely eliminated. (White’s pawn on g2 also prevents any interposition there.) White will be forced to play Kg3–g2. (After which our winning attack continues.)

So as Black, our move is:

  make_move f2g4

This is the move I recommend.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

This move develops the knight to a more central post without walking into tactical liability (for instance, note that other knight moves like Nd4–c2 or Nd4–b3 fall prey to a direct capture by White’s queen on d1 or by the pawn on f5). Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play as Black. I’d like to see some forcing intent, so I’ll try a move that checks White’s exposed king. Looking at the board, notice that White’s king on g4 lies on the diagonal where a pawn push could attack it. In fact, Black’s pawn on f7 can advance two squares to f5. From f7, moving to f5 is legal (the f6 square is free), and when it lands on f5 its capture moves (diagonally “forward” for Black) cover e4 and g4. Since the White king is on g4, this move puts White in check—and unlike a similar idea with the pawn on h7, White cannot capture on f5 because the knight on h4 guards that square (remember: from h4 the knight controls f5 among other squares).

So my move is:

make_move f7f5

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one of the most forcing moves is to activate the rook on f4. Moving that rook vertically to f5 creates an immediate check on the white king (which is on g5, sharing rank 5 with the rook on f5). There are no intervening pieces between f5 and g5, so the white king is directly attacked along the fifth rank.

Thus, I'll make the move:

make_move f4f5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one idea I'm considering is to bring the rook over to the a‐file to immediately check the white king. In our diagram the rook currently sits on b4. By playing

  make_move b4a4

we place the rook on a4 so that it controls the entire a‑file. Since the lone white king is on a5, it immediately finds itself in check (because the rook on a4 now sees a5 along the a‑file).

Looking more deeply: after 1...Ra4 the white king’s adjacent escape squares are:
 • a6 is covered by the bishop on c8 (since from c8 its down–left diagonal goes to b7 then a6).
 • b6 is attacked by our knight on d5 (remember, from d5 the knight can hop to b6).
 • b4 was under the knight’s control even before (from d5 the knight reaches b4).
That leaves b5 and a4 as possible moves. But a4 is now occupied by our rook. (If white tries to capture our rook on a4, then we’ll have a material advantage and a winning position.) White might try Kb5, but then we’ll have a very dominant position and keep driving the king into a mating net.

So with all considerations in mind, I’m going to play

  make_move b4a4

Your move!

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

make_move d1c3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board position you provided, one very strong candidate for black is to deliver a check with the queen. In particular, moving the queen from f3 to c3 (that is, “make_move f3c3”) does the following:

• It gives check along the c3–d2 diagonal (since from c3 the queen’s diagonal covers d2, where white’s king sits).

• It lands on c3—a square that is additionally covered by your knight on a4 (remember, the knight from a4 attacks c3 along one of its L‐shaped moves). This means that even though c3 is adjacent to the white king, white cannot capture your queen without moving into the knight’s attack.

In UCI notation, the move is: f3c3

I will now play that move.

make_move f3c3

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll start by inspecting the board. One way to read the board is with rank 8 at the top and rank 1 at the bottom; note that Black’s major pieces occupy the top two ranks while White has only a king (on h2) and three pawns (on b3, e4, h3).

Here’s a brief rundown:
• Rank 8: Black rook on a8, black king on e8, black bishop on f8, and black rook on h8.
• Rank 7: Black pawns on a7, b7, e7, f7, g7, and h7.
• Other Black pieces: a pawn on b5 (rank 5); a pawn on d4 and a knight on h4 (rank 4); and the black queen on e1 (rank 1).
• White’s king stands on h2 and White has pawns on b3, e4, and h3.

Because White’s king is nearly trapped (its only adjacent squares are g1, g2, h1, and g3 – with h3 occupied by its own pawn) we can try a forcing attack.

I’ve found a very neat mating idea:
1. First, deliver a check with the queen by playing Qe1–f2. (In UCI format that is “e1f2”.) 

  Why Qe1–f2+? 
  – From f2 the queen controls the entire rank 2 (covering g2 and h2) and also its diagonals hit g1 and g3.
  – White’s king on h2 cannot go to g1, g2, or g3 because those squares are covered by the queen.
  – The only legal king move is to retreat to h1.

2. Then, after White is forced 1…Kh1, Black can deliver mate with a knight move: Nh4–f3#. (Because from f3 the knight covers h2 and g1 while the queen on f2 still covers g2, leaving the white king on h1 with no escape.)

White cannot interpose or capture the checking queen on f2 (since f2 is not adjacent to h2) so this two‐move sequence wins immediately.

Since it is Black’s turn now, I will deliver the initiating check. (The forced mate sequence will follow once White plays the only move, Kh1.)

Therefore, my move is: 

  make_move e1f2

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play as Black. I notice that my bishop on e4 is targeted by White’s knight on g5 (since N from g5 can jump to e4). To avoid the exchange and retain the overwhelming advantage I have (with two rooks, two bishops, and a full pawn army versus White’s lone knight, bishop, and a couple of pawns), I’ll reposition that bishop.

A natural, safe move is to retreat the bishop from e4 to f5. This diagonal step (e4–f5) moves the bishop off the g5 knight’s immediate reach while keeping it active along useful diagonals.

So my move is: make_move e4f5

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board’s current layout, one candidate checking move is to bring the rook on f7 down to f5. (Recall that White’s only piece is the king sitting on h5.) Moving the rook from f7 to f5 places it on the 5th rank where it directly eyes h5 along the clear row and delivers a check. 

To explain briefly:
• The rook from f7 travels vertically down to f5 (the f6 square is free).
• Once on f5, it attacks every square along rank 5—including h5, where White’s king sits.
• Given the surrounding control (the bishop on e3 covers f4, g5, and h6, and the pawns on g7 and h7 already restrict some adjacent squares), this check forces the White king into limited options (g4 or h4).

Thus, a solid and forcing move is:

make_move f7f5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one strong candidate is to bring the rook closer to the enemy king. In this setup the white king on f1 is already hemmed in by our bishop on e3 (which covers f2 and g1) so that, with the right rook move on the first rank, the white king’s escape options are extremely limited.

One concrete idea is to play:

  make_move h3h1

This move puts our rook on h1 along the first rank, checking the white king. After R h1+, the white king’s adjacent squares are:

• e1 – now attacked along the 1st rank by the rook on h1;
• g1 – doubly covered by our rook on h1 and the bishop on e3;
• f2 – covered by the bishop on e3.

That leaves only e2 and g2 as possible escapes. Although the mate isn’t immediate, the white king is forced into a very restricted set of moves and we can then coordinate our remaining pieces (e.g. our other rook coming along the f‑file or our king/bishop) to deliver mate in the near future.

So I’ll proceed with the move:

make_move h3h1

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll opt for a king move that prepares a decisive pawn promotion. In the current position the pawn on d2 is ready to promote, but promoting immediately would let White’s king capture the new piece (since White’s king on c2 controls d1). To prevent that, I can reposition my king so that it protects d1. Moving the king from e3 to e2 controls d1 (since the squares adjacent to e2 include d1), meaning that when I later push the pawn to d1 (promoting it), White won’t be able to capture the promoted piece without moving adjacent to my king (an illegal king move).

Thus, my move as Black will be:

make_move e3e2

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one tactical idea stands out. Notice that the black knight sitting on b4 has a powerful opportunity. It can jump to c2, capturing White’s pawn on c2 and – more importantly – forking the White king on e1 and the rook waiting on a1. The knight on c2 would be defended by the Black bishop on f5 (since the bishop’s diagonal from f5 reaches c2), so if White attempts to capture the knight to get rid of the check, Black’s reply Bxc2 would win the queen (or gain decisive material).

Thus, I’m going to play:

make_move b4c2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current position, one move that immediately wins material is to capture White’s pawn on c4 with Black’s d5‐pawn. In other words, Black can play d5xc4 (UCI notation: "d5c4"). Notice that:

• The pawn on d5 (located on the 5th rank, file d) can capture diagonally to c4.
• The pawn on c4 is “en prise” because none of White’s pieces can recapture immediately—White’s f1‐bishop is blocked by the pawn on e2, and the knight on a2 cannot jump there.
• Winning this pawn not only improves Black’s material edge—especially given Black’s extra pieces—but also opens lines for further piece activity while keeping White’s already cramped position in check.

Ready to proceed, my move is:

make_move d5c4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play  h4e1 — moving my queen from h4 to e1, giving an immediate check. 

To explain briefly: from h4 the queen can go diagonally to e1. In the resulting position the white king on d1 finds all its adjacent escape squares covered (with c2 under attack from my bishop on d3 and both d2 and e2 coming under the queen’s control), so white’s only legal reply is to capture the queen with the king. This sequence forces white into a very unfavorable position, and I’ll be able to follow up strongly. 

(make_move h4e1)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

This move delivers a check along the second rank. Notice that after Qf2, white’s king (on h2) cannot capture the queen because the queen isn’t adjacent, and many escape squares (g2, g3, and g1) become covered by the queen’s horizontal, vertical, and diagonal control. White’s only viable moves are shifting the king to h1 or h3, after which I’ll quickly intensify my attack with my extra forces.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play a knight fork. I notice that my knight on d4 can capture the white pawn on c2 with check, and from c2 it will fork White’s king on e1 and rook on a1. This move forces White to respond by moving the king (since capturing the knight with the queen is very unfavorable), after which I can capture the rook on a1. This wins material for Black.

I'll therefore play:

make_move d4c2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board position, one promising idea is to use our queen not only to keep control of the center but also to immediately give a check. For example, by moving the queen from f4 to g4 (i.e. "make_move f4g4") we step onto a square that lines up with the white king along the g‑file. Since the white king sits on g2 (with only g3 lying between), the queen on g4 delivers an immediate check. White’s options will then be limited to king moves (since neither the knight nor the pawn can interpose effectively).

Before committing though, let’s verify a few points:
 • The 1‑square horizontal move from f4 to g4 is unobstructed (g4 is empty).
 • With the queen on g4, the g‑file is controlled (g3, g2, g1, etc.) and white’s king, on g2, is in check.
 • The white knight on f3 does not have access to g4 (its legal moves from f3 are d4, d2, e5, e1, g5, g1, h4, and h2), so it can’t capture our queen.
 • After the check the white king’s possible moves are forced into one of the adjacent safe squares, allowing us to further consolidate our attack.

Given our huge material edge and the forcing nature of the check, “make_move f4g4” looks very good.

Thus, I’ll now complete my turn with:

make_move f4g4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board you provided, I notice that the white knight sitting on c3 (the ♘ in the third rank, third file) is currently challenged by our pieces. In fact, one of our knights—currently on e4—can jump to c3 (via a legal “L‐shaped” move: from e4 to c3 is (–2, –1) in file–rank differences) and capture that white knight. After 1...e4c3, white’s only recapture available is to have the pawn from b2 capture our knight (since from b2 a pawn can capture diagonally onto c3). That exchange would remove white’s sole knight while our knight from d4 remains untouched—improving our minor‐piece balance and potentially leaving white with a slightly compromised queenside structure.

Thus, I’m going to make the move:
make_move e4c3

I’ll opt for a tactical blow. Looking at the board, my knight on c3 may jump to d1—which is occupied by the white queen. (Recall that although the symbol on d1 looks like a black queen, by context it’s white’s queen.) The move  c3d1 is legal for a knight (moving one file right and two ranks down) and captures the queen, netting a decisive material win (even if white recaptures, I’ll be up the exchange).

Thus, I’ll play:

make_move c3d1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board—with your queen currently on g5 and white’s king unusually exposed on e4—a forcing move is to give an immediate check. One candidate is to move your queen one square down the g‑file: from g5 to g4. In UCI format that move is written as:

make_move g5g4

This move puts the white king in check along the fourth rank (since white’s king on e4 and your queen on g4 lie along the rank with the intermediate square f4 empty), forcing white to move the king (blocking isn’t feasible as no white piece can legally occupy f4 to interpose). With the king forced to move, you can then continue developing your pieces (for example, develop your knight from b8 to c6) to exploit the exposed white king.

I’ll now play:

make_move g5g4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one very sharp candidate for Black is to use the knight on e4 to initiate a tactical sequence. In particular, moving that knight from e4 to f2 (with the move “e4f2”) gives check and simultaneously attacks the white rook on h1. White’s best response is almost forced—if White simply moves the king, Black will capture the rook immediately, winning material. In practice, White must capture with the knight on h3 (since h3 → f2 is a natural L‐move), and after that Black can follow up with a move like bringing the knight from b4 into action (for example, playing …N(b4)a2 to capture the pawn on a2 and, after a recapture by White’s rook, win the exchange).

Thus, the immediate, forcing move is to play:

make_move e4f2

To explain briefly: Moving the queen diagonally from a5 to e1 puts the white king on g1 in check. The white king’s adjacent squares are either occupied by its own pawns or are controlled by my pieces—in fact, after Qe1+ the only legal response for White is to block the check by moving the bishop from e2 to f1. Then I can finish with 2...Nxf1#, as my knight from g3 can capture the blocking bishop on f1 (a legal knight move from g3) and leave the white king with no escape squares.

So now I’ll complete my turn with:

make_move a5e1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll opt for a queen move. My reasoning is as follows:

I notice that my queen on a6 can become very active along a diagonal. In particular, by playing Qc4 (which in UCI format is “a6c4”), my queen will attack along the diagonal that passes through d3 and e2. This immediately eyes White’s knight on e2—a central piece that quickly needs safeguarding. White isn’t in a position to block that diagonal (for example, the pawn on b3 blocks the queen’s access to defending the knight on a4 along the opposite diagonal), so White will be forced to move the knight on e2. In many lines, after the knight is forced off its post, I can generate further pressure in the center and on the queenside.

So I’ll play:

make_move a6c4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll start by playing the forcing move 1… Qf3–c3+.

This move gives check and forces White’s king—whose only legal reply is to go from b4 to b5—into a very narrow escape route. (After Qf3–c3+ the White king’s other adjacent squares are all covered by the queen on c3.) With White’s king displaced, I can follow up with a second decisive checking move (for example, 2… Qd1–b3+ keeps the pressure on and will soon lead to mate).

Therefore, I now choose:

make_move f3c3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one promising idea is to use the active light‐squared bishop on c5 to remove one of White’s undeveloped “kingside” defenders. In our current setup the White knight sitting on g1 isn’t defended by any nearby unit. (Notice that the king on e1 is too far away to protect g1 and the queen on d1 can’t reach there along a clear line.) Therefore a forcing exchange with

  Bishop from c5 takes on g1

seems attractive. In UCI notation that move is written as

  make_move c5g1

After 1...c5g1, White’s almost forced response is to recapture with the rook from h1 (since leaving the bishop on g1 would be very unpleasant), and the resulting exchange (bishop for knight) leaves White with a less harmonious kingside. This gives Black good prospects to pursue an initiative.

I will now play

  make_move c5g1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board—and noting that Black is clearly ahead in material—a good way to simplify and reduce White’s counterplay is to exchange a knight. In this position the Black knight on e4 can capture the White knight on c3 with the move “e4c3.” After 1...e4c3, if White recaptures (for example with the bishop from b2), many of White’s active pieces will be traded off, which tends to favor the side with a material advantage.

Therefore, I will proceed with the move:

make_move e4c3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board you provided, I'll analyze the position briefly. We have the following pieces (using standard board orientation with rank 8 at the top and rank 1 at the bottom):

• Row 2 (rank 7): Black pawns on a7, b7, c7  
• Row 3 (rank 6): Black king on g6  
• Row 5 (rank 4): Black pawns on e4 and f4, and the White king on g4  
• Row 6 (rank 3): A Black pawn on g3  

As Black, you have several pawn moves available and king moves that remain legal, but one feature stands out: your pawn on g3 is already advanced (on rank 3) and only two moves away from promotion. By pushing it one step further to g2, you create an immediate threat of queening on the next move. The white king on g4 is too far (not adjacent to g2) to capture this pawn immediately.

Thus, I choose to push the pawn from g3 to g2.

make_move g3g2

I'll choose to play the move "g1g3". This moves the queen vertically from g1 to g3. Notice that from g3 the queen sits on the top‐left diagonal (g3–f4–e5–d6–…), so it immediately gives check to the white king on e5. No white piece can capture or block adequately (the white king cannot capture the queen because g3 is two steps away), and it forces white to respond.

make_move g1g3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board we have, here’s the situation:

• The board is oriented so that rank 8 is the top row and rank 1 is the bottom row. Files run from a–h from left to right.
• Black’s pieces are as follows:
 – A pawn on a5 (row 4, column a) and a pawn on b5 (row 4, column b).
 – The queen on d5.
 – The king on b3.
• White’s only piece is the king on f2 (row 7, column f).

As Black we’re looking to use our overwhelming material advantage (queen and pawns, with our king safely away) to force the opposing lone king into a mating net. A forcing check that limits White’s king options is a good start.

One candidate is the move Qd5–d2. When the queen moves from d5 to d2:
 • It lands on d2 (file d, rank 2) which, along with its inherent queen powers, immediately gives check along the second rank.
 • White’s king on f2, being on rank 2 as well, is now attacked along that rank. In fact, because the queen on d2 controls the entire second rank (including e2, f2, g2, etc.) and it also covers nearby diagonals (for example, it hits e1 via a SE diagonal), White’s king is forced into one of only a few squares (namely f1, g1, f3, or g3).
 • Importantly, note that since the white king would have to step away (and cannot capture the queen from f2 because the jump from f2 to d2 is two squares away), this move maintains the initiative and restricts White’s options further.

Thus, as Black, I will now deliver the check with the queen from d5 to d2.

make_move d5d2

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, a key observation is that white’s only minor piece—the knight sitting on e1—is vulnerable. Meanwhile, note that one of our knights (on f2) is currently “loose” (undefended) and could be captured by the white king if we’re not careful. In order to simplify into an obviously winning endgame (black having queen, rooks, both bishops and at least one knight versus white’s lonely king and pawn) and to avoid letting white snatch our knight on f2 for free, a good plan is to put our queen on a square that not only keeps her active but also defends that knight.

Here’s the reasoning:
1. Our queen on a5 is eyeing the e1 square along the diagonal (a5–b4–c3–d2–e1) and could capture the white knight on e1—but if we did Qxe1 immediately, our queen would end up on e1 and would no longer be in a position to help protect our knight on f2. That, in turn, would allow white’s king (currently on g2) to capture our knight on f2 (since g2 is adjacent to f2), which is best avoided when we have a winning advantage.
2. By playing Qd2 (queen moves from a5 to d2), we use the diagonal route (a5–b4–c3–d2) and land on d2. From d2 the queen defends the entire second rank—including f2, where our other knight sits—and keeps an eye on the critical diagonal.
3. This prophylactic move means that after Qd2 white can’t simply capture our knight on f2 with the king. On a future move we can then capture the white knight on e1 with our knight from c2 (with the move c2e1) without worrying about leaving f2 undefended.

Given this plan and the overwhelming material advantage we already hold, the best move is:

make_move a5d2

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

♟ ♟ ♟ ⭘ ♝ ♟ ⭘ ♟
⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♟ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play the pawn from e5 to e4. This move not only advances a central pawn but also immediately attacks the white knight on d3 via the pawn’s diagonal (since from e4 it would capture any piece on d3). It gains time by forcing White to move the knight and strengthens Black’s central control.

make_move e5e4

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play 1... Qf3+ (in UCI notation: “f2f3”). 

Here's the idea behind the move:

• My queen on f2 moves to f3 and checks the white king on h1 along the diagonal (since f3 and h1 lie two squares apart in both file and rank).  
• This check forces White’s king to step off h1 (its only legal moves being Kg1 or Kh2) without being able to capture my queen (since f3 isn’t adjacent to h1).  
• Once the king is forced to move, I’ll continue to simplify (for example by eventually grabbing the lone white pawn on a2), and with my material advantage remaining I’ll easily convert the win.

So my move is: make_move f2f3.
